alvatore, Antonino, Nichola, Pasquale, Piera, Raffaela, Rocco.","Italian (southern; also <b>Lobosco</b>): variant of   Bosco  , with the addition of the definite article <i>lo</i>."]}]},{"name":"Matthew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathew","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Matthew ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matthew de Bosco was born about 1280, in Tankersley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard de Bosco  Wood, was 21 and his mother, Bosco, was 12. He had at least 1 daughter with Bosco. He died in 1376, at the age of 97."},"et":{"about 1280–about 1376":"umbes 1280–1376","1280–1376":"1280–1376","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1312–1343":"1312–1343","1260–1316":"1260–1316","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1316":"1316","about 1280":"umbes 1280","after 1316":"pärast 1316","1312":"1312","1343":"1343","1376":"1376","about 1376":"1376","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Tankersley,Yorkshire,England.":"Tankersley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tankersley, Yorkshire, England":"Tankersley, Yorkshire, England","Thornhill, Yorkshire, England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1280–about 1376":"n